Port uu_chmod 0.8.0 to a NATIVE in-process brush builtin, like uu_cp, so a box
(and build/install recipes) run chmod IN-PROCESS. Two divergences, both local to
vendor/uu_chmod:

* Logical I/O: a new entry chmod_main(args, cwd, out, err) runs on the builtin's
  worker thread writing the shell's logical sinks, never the process's fd 1/2.
  The verbose/changes println! sites route to a thread-local CHMOD_OUT buffer via
  a crate-local chmod_out! macro; uucore show!/show_error! are shadowed to
  CHMOD_ERR; the bare set_exit_code(1) sites are shadowed to defer onto a
  thread-local CHMOD_EXIT. The entry drains the buffers and surfaces the status.
* Logical cwd: brush never chdir's the process, so the shared run(args, cwd) body
  resolves every relative file operand and the --reference RFILE against the
  shell's logical cwd before the chmod walk.

The standalone #[uucore::main] uumain bridge is retained (drains to real stdio),
so the binary path is unchanged.

